<DOC><DOCNO> AP891206-0171 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-12-06-89 0209EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f BC-IBMCuts-History     12-06 0208</FIRST><SECOND>BC-IBM Cuts-History,0214</SECOND><HEAD>Latest Job Cuts Are Fourth Program Since 1986</HEAD><HEAD>With PM-Computer Slump, Bjt</HEAD><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Here is a history of job-cutting programs atInternational Business Machines Corp. since 1986.   September 1986: IBM announces retirement incentives that addfive years to the age and five years to the length of service ofeligible employees for purposes of calculating retirement benefits.By the end of 1987, 15,000 employees accept the incentives,including 13,000 in the United States.   June 1988: IBM announces separation incentives aimed atmanufacturing and development employees in Tucson, Ariz., and BocaRaton, Fla., and at headquarters employees across the UnitedStates. About 7,000 U.S. employees accept.   September 1989: IBM announces separation incentives to employeesin selected skill groups in Owego and Endicott, N.Y., Lexington,Ky., and Manassas, Va. The company expects 600 to 1,000 to acceptby the end of 1989.   December 1989: IBM announces it will offer separation incentivesaimed at cutting 10,000 U.S. employees, mainly in staff and supportfunctions. Employees who accept will receive one week's salary foreach six months of service, up to a maximum of 52 weeks of salary.The company says most of the employees are expected to leave in thefirst half of 1990.</TEXT></DOC>